# TypeScript: Use Type Instead of Interface

Always use `type` declarations instead of `interface` declarations in this project.

## Rules

- ❌ **Never** use `interface` keyword
- ✅ **Always** use `type` keyword for object type definitions
- ✅ Use `type` for React component props
- ✅ Use `type` for function return types and parameters

## Examples

### Component Props

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
interface ButtonProps {
  label: string;
  onClick: () => void;
}

// ✅ GOOD
type ButtonProps = {
  label: string;
  onClick: () => void;
};
```

### Type Definitions

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
}

// ✅ GOOD
type User = {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  email: string;
};
```

### Context Types

```typescript
// ❌ BAD
interface PhotoContextType {
  state: PhotoState;
  setState: (state: PhotoState) => void;
}

// ✅ GOOD
type PhotoContextType = {
  state: PhotoState;
  setState: (state: PhotoState) => void;
};
```

## Type Composition

Types support all the same features as interfaces:

```typescript
// Extending types
type BaseProps = {
  id: string;
};

type ExtendedProps = BaseProps & {
  name: string;
};

// Union types (types are more flexible)
type Status = "pending" | "success" | "error";

// Intersection types
type Props = ButtonProps & ThemeProps;
```
